---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const siteName = import.meta.env.PUBLIC_SITE_NAME ?? "PricingNest";
---
<BaseLayout
  title={`Pricing Experiments Playbook | ${siteName}`}
  description="A practical playbook for price increases and annual prepay experiments with metrics, segmentation, and guardrails."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <h1>Pricing experiments playbook</h1>
    <p>
      Pricing changes are easiest to reverse when you run them as controlled experiments. Use this playbook to define a
      hypothesis, pick guardrails, and measure outcomes without breaking trust.
    </p>
  </section>

  <div class="grid">
    <article class="card col8">
      <h2>1) Segment before you change prices</h2>
      <ul class="list">
        <li>Segment by plan, customer size, and acquisition channel.</li>
        <li>Separate new customers from existing customers (grandfathering reduces churn risk).</li>
        <li>Track price sensitivity proxies (usage intensity, feature adoption, support load).</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">2) Define success metrics and guardrails</h2>
      <ul class="list">
        <li><strong>Primary</strong>: revenue per account, gross profit, conversion rate, churn (gross/net).</li>
        <li><strong>Guardrails</strong>: refund rate, support tickets, time‑to‑value, activation.</li>
        <li>Measure by cohort and keep the window long enough for billing cycles.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">3) Run a price increase safely</h2>
      <ul class="list">
        <li>Start with new customers; then expand to renewals with clear communication.</li>
        <li>Consider feature‑based packaging changes when value delivery is uneven.</li>
        <li>Use break‑even churn as a sanity check, then model best/base/worst scenarios.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">4) Annual prepay experiments</h2>
      <ul class="list">
        <li>Offer annual discounts where commitment reduces churn or collection overhead.</li>
        <li>Compare effective monthly rate and cash flow separately (they are different benefits).</li>
        <li>Watch cohort retention: annual buyers often behave differently from monthly buyers.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">Tools to use</h2>
      <ul class="list">
        <li><a href="/saas-pricing/pricing-increase-impact-calculator/">Pricing increase impact calculator</a></li>
        <li><a href="/saas-pricing/annual-discount-calculator/">Annual discount calculator</a></li>
        <li><a href="/saas-pricing/churn-impact-calculator/">Churn impact calculator</a></li>
      </ul>
    </article>

    <aside class="card col4">
      <h2>Tip</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        Treat pricing as a product surface. Document assumptions, communicate clearly, and keep grandfathering rules
        simple.
      </p>
      <h2 style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">Next</h2>
      <ul class="list">
        <li><a href="/saas-pricing/use-cases/pricing-experiments/">Use case: pricing experiments</a></li>
        <li><a href="/saas-pricing/">Browse calculators</a></li>
      </ul>
    </aside>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

